Baezy Bot Privacy Policy

Effective Date: July 20, 2026
Bot Name: Baezy
Prefix: !
Current Version: Beta 0.7.0

1. Introduction

This Privacy Policy explains what information Baezy may access, process, store, or display while operating in Discord servers.

Baezy is a custom Discord bot designed to provide community tools, moderation features, reaction roles, Twitch go-live notifications, utility commands, entertainment commands, and server-management support.

By using Baezy, interacting with Baezy, or allowing Baezy to operate in a Discord server, you acknowledge that Baezy may process certain Discord-related information as described in this Privacy Policy.

2. Scope of This Policy

This Privacy Policy applies to Baezy’s operation within Discord servers where it has been added.

This policy covers:

Commands sent to Baezy
Messages Baezy can access for enabled features
Reaction-role interactions
Moderation actions performed through Baezy
Deleted-message logging, if enabled
Auto-role assignment
Twitch go-live notification features
Data stored locally by Baezy
Bot runtime logs and troubleshooting information

This policy does not control Discord’s own collection or use of data. Discord’s own Terms of Service and Privacy Policy apply separately.

3. Information Baezy May Access

Depending on the server configuration, bot permissions, and features used, Baezy may access or process the following types of information:

Discord User Information

Baezy may process:

Discord user IDs
Usernames
Display names
Server nicknames
Avatar URLs
Bot account status
Account creation dates
Server join dates
Role membership
Permission information
Boosting status, where available
Whether a user is a server member, where available

This information may be used by commands such as !uinfo, !id, !roleinfo, moderation commands, reaction roles, auto-role systems, and logging features.

Discord Server Information

Baezy may process:

Server IDs
Server names
Member counts
Owner information
Channel IDs
Channel names
Role IDs
Role names
Role colors
Role permissions
Server-specific command context

This information may be used for server information commands, moderation tools, reaction roles, role assignment, logging, and troubleshooting.

Message Information

Baezy may process message-related information when needed for bot features.

This may include:

Message content sent as bot commands
Message IDs
Channel IDs where commands are used
Attachments included with commands
Links or text included in commands
Poll questions and options
Embed titles and descriptions
Content passed into administrative posting commands such as !speak or !embed

Baezy may also process deleted-message content if deleted-message logging is enabled in the server.

4. Information Baezy May Store

Baezy may store limited information locally on the server where the bot is hosted.

Stored data may include:

Moderation Logs

Baezy may store moderation case data in files such as:

data/modlogs.json

Moderation logs may include:

Case ID
Moderation action type
Target user ID
Target username
Moderator user ID
Moderator username
Reason provided
Timestamp
Extra case details, such as channel ID, duration, or previous ban reason

This data is used for moderation history commands such as !case, !cases, !modlogs, and !history.

VIP / Member of the Day History

Baezy may store Member of the Day or VIP selection history in files such as:

data/vip_history.json

This may include:

Server ID
Server name
Selected user ID
Selected username or display name
Selecting administrator ID
Selecting administrator username
Timestamp

This is used to prevent the same member from being selected again within the configured cooldown period.

Restart Notices

Baezy may temporarily store restart-related information in files such as:

data/restart_notice.json

This may include:

Channel ID where restart was requested
User ID of the requester
Timestamp or restart context

This data is temporary and is used so Baezy can post a confirmation message after restarting.

Reaction Role Configuration

Reaction-role mappings may be stored in code or configuration. These mappings may include:

Message IDs
Emoji characters or custom emoji IDs
Role IDs

Baezy uses this information to assign or remove roles when users add or remove reactions.

Runtime Logs

Baezy may generate runtime logs through system logs or service journals.

Logs may include:

Startup messages
Cog loading messages
Error messages
Permission failures
Twitch API errors
Reaction-role success or failure messages
Auto-role success or failure messages
Moderation logging errors
Debugging or troubleshooting output

These logs are used for maintenance, debugging, security review, and stability monitoring.

5. Deleted Message Logging

If enabled, Baezy may log deleted messages to a configured Discord channel.

Deleted-message logs may include:

Original message author
Original author user ID
Channel where the message was deleted
Channel ID
Message ID
Deleted message text content, if available
Attachment links, if available
Timestamp of the log entry

Discord does not always provide complete information about message deletion events. Baezy may not be able to determine who deleted a message unless additional audit-log-based functionality is enabled.

Deleted-message logging should only be used by server owners or administrators who understand and accept the privacy implications of logging deleted content.

Server administrators are responsible for informing their community if deleted-message logging is active where required by server rules, platform expectations, or applicable law.

6. Command Processing

When users run Baezy commands, Baezy may process the command text and related Discord context.

For example:

!uinfo may process a user mention or user ID
!ban may process a target user ID and reason
!timeout may process a target member, duration, and reason
!poll may process poll questions and options
!speak may process a target channel and message content
!embed may process a target channel, title, color, and description
!color may process a hex code or color request
!reaction roles functionality may process reaction events

Command data is generally used only to complete the requested command. Some command data may be stored if it is part of moderation logs, VIP history, restart notices, or other persistent bot features.

7. Role Assignment Data

Baezy may process role assignment events for features such as:

Auto-role assignment when a user joins
Reaction roles
Moderation role checks
Permission-based command access

For these features, Baezy may process:

User IDs
Server IDs
Role IDs
Reaction emoji IDs or emoji text
Message IDs for reaction-role messages

Baezy does not use role data for advertising or profiling. Role data is used only to perform server-management functions.

8. Twitch Data

Baezy may use the Twitch API to check whether configured Twitch streamers are live.

Baezy may process Twitch-related data such as:

Twitch streamer login names
Stream IDs
Stream titles
Stream categories or games
Viewer counts
Stream thumbnails
Twitch stream URLs

This data is used to post go-live notifications in configured Discord channels.

Baezy does not collect Twitch account credentials from ordinary Discord users. Twitch API credentials used by the bot are configured privately by the bot operator and should not be shared publicly.

9. Attachments and Media

Some Baezy commands may process attachments or media.

For example:

!speak may copy uploaded attachments and repost them in a selected channel
!shesaid may post a local GIF asset
Embed commands may include links or text supplied by administrators

When attachments are copied through Baezy, the bot processes the attachment only as needed to complete the requested command.

Users should not submit sensitive, private, or confidential files to Baezy unless they understand where the bot will repost them.

10. What Baezy Does Not Intentionally Collect

Baezy does not intentionally collect:

Passwords
Payment card numbers
Government identification numbers
Private Discord direct messages
Discord account login credentials
Full Discord account profiles beyond what Discord exposes to bots
Sensitive personal information unrelated to bot functionality

Baezy should not be used to request, store, or transmit sensitive personal information.

Users and administrators should avoid entering private or sensitive data into bot commands.

11. Direct Messages

Baezy is primarily designed to operate inside Discord servers.

Unless specifically configured otherwise, Baezy does not rely on private direct messages for its main features.

If a user sends a direct message to Baezy, the bot may receive that message through Discord, but Baezy may not respond or may only process it according to available bot functionality.

Users should not send sensitive information to Baezy through direct messages.

12. Data Sharing

Baezy does not sell personal data.

Baezy may share or transmit information only as needed for normal operation, including:

Sending messages, embeds, logs, and role changes through Discord
Checking Twitch stream status through Twitch’s API
Storing runtime logs on the hosting server
Allowing the bot owner or authorized maintainer to review logs for troubleshooting

Baezy’s data may also be processed by infrastructure providers used to host or operate the bot, such as the server hosting provider.

13. Access to Stored Data

Stored Baezy data may be accessible to:

The bot owner
Authorized maintainers
Server administrators with access to configured log channels
Users with permission to run relevant commands, such as moderation history commands
Hosting infrastructure administrators, where technically applicable

Access should be limited to people who need it for moderation, operation, security, or maintenance.

14. Data Retention

Baezy retains data only as long as needed for the feature or administrative purpose involved.

Examples:

Moderation logs may be retained until manually deleted or archived
VIP history may be retained to enforce cooldowns and preserve history
Restart notice data is temporary and may be deleted after restart confirmation
Runtime logs may be retained according to server or system journal settings
Reaction-role mappings may remain as long as the reaction-role system is active
Deleted-message logs may remain in Discord channels until manually removed according to server policy

Server owners or bot operators are responsible for setting retention practices appropriate for their community.

15. Data Removal Requests

Users may request removal of data associated with them where technically possible.

Depending on the type of data, removal may need to be performed by:

The bot owner
A server administrator
A moderator with access to relevant Discord channels
The hosting server operator

Some data may be difficult or impossible to fully remove if it exists in:

Discord audit logs
Discord message history
Server backups
System logs
Moderation records needed for server safety
Third-party platform logs

Requests should be directed to the server owner, bot owner, or appropriate administrative contact.

16. Security

Baezy’s operator should take reasonable steps to protect bot data and credentials.

Recommended security practices include:

Keeping .env private
Never sharing the Discord bot token publicly
Regenerating tokens immediately if exposed
Limiting server access to trusted maintainers
Restricting powerful commands to trusted users
Keeping Baezy’s role below only necessary administrative roles
Avoiding unnecessary bot permissions
Reviewing logs after crashes or permission errors
Backing up important data files before major changes

No system is perfectly secure, and Baezy is provided on a best-effort basis.

17. Children and Age Requirements

Baezy operates on Discord and is intended for use by Discord users who meet Discord’s age requirements.

Baezy does not knowingly collect information from users outside the context of normal Discord server operation.

Server owners are responsible for managing their communities in accordance with Discord’s rules and any applicable age-related requirements.

18. International Users

Baezy may be used in Discord servers with users from different regions.

By using Baezy, users acknowledge that information may be processed through Discord, Twitch, the bot’s hosting provider, and the bot’s operating server, which may be located in different jurisdictions.

Server owners should consider applicable privacy obligations for their own communities.

19. Third-Party Services

Baezy depends on third-party services for operation.

These may include:

Discord, for messages, roles, servers, reactions, moderation actions, and bot interactions
Twitch, for stream live-status checks and stream metadata
Hosting providers, for running the bot and storing runtime files/logs

These third-party services have their own terms and privacy policies. Baezy does not control how those third parties process data.

20. Changes to This Privacy Policy

This Privacy Policy may be updated as Baezy changes.

Updates may occur when:

New commands are added
New logging features are added
Data storage behavior changes
Twitch or Discord integrations change
Security or moderation systems change
Documentation is updated

Continued use of Baezy after changes are published means you acknowledge the updated Privacy Policy.

21. Contact

For privacy questions, data removal requests, bug reports, or concerns about Baezy, contact the bot owner or server administrator responsible for the server where Baezy is installed.

For servers directly managed by Baezy’s owner, contact the bot owner through the appropriate Discord support or administrative channel.
